{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"33c2ee93-5da3-4460-a55a-174f66045396","content":"Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your scenario directly:\n\n## 1. JSON column type: `nvarchar(max)` → `nvarchar(4000)`\n\nWith `UseAzureSql()`, EF Core 10 defaults primitive collections and owned-type JSON columns to `nvarchar(4000)` instead of `nvarchar(max)`. Running `migrations add` will emit `AlterColumn` calls to shrink every existing JSON column. If any row exceeds 4000 characters, the migration will fail at runtime.\n\n**Fix** — pin the old type in `OnModelCreating`:\n\n```csharp\n// Per property\nb.Property(e => e.Tags).HasColumnType(\"nvarchar(max)\");\n\n// Or globally via a convention\nconfigurationBuilder\n    .DefaultTypeMapping<string[]>()\n    .HasColumnType(\"nvarchar(max)\");\n```\n\n## 2. `Contains()` translation: untyped OPENJSON → typed OPENJSON\n\nIn EF Core 9, `list.Contains(e.Id)` translated to:\n\n```sql\nWHERE e.Id IN (SELECT CAST([value] AS int) FROM OPENJSON(@p))\n```\n\nEF Core 10 uses a **typed** `WITH` clause:\n\n```sql\nWHERE e.Id IN (SELECT [value] FROM OPENJSON(@p) WITH ([value] int '$'))\n```\n\nThis changes query plans. The typed variant lets SQL Server use statistics/indexes more effectively in most cases, but **existing plan-sensitive code or query hints may break**. Test critical queries and check execution plans after upgrading.\n\n## 3. Multi-target + `dotnet ef` without `--framework`\n\nWhen a project multi-targets (`<TargetFrameworks>net9.0;net10.0</TargetFrameworks>`), EF Core 10 tooling **no longer silently picks the first framework**—it errors out:\n\n```\nYour project targets multiple frameworks. Specify which to use with --framework.\n```\n\n**Fix** — always pass the flag:\n\n```bash\ndotnet ef migrations add MyMigration --framework net10.0\n```\n\nOr set a default in your `.csproj` for design-time:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"'$(EFDefaultFramework)' == ''\">\n  <TargetFramework>net10.0</TargetFramework>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n---\n\n**Priority order**: #1 is the most dangerous (data-truncation risk at migration time), #3 will break CI immediately, and #2 is a silent behavioral change to watch in production query perf.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bcb63fa3-d316-4c5d-ba12-aeb2ee26a234","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about EF Core 10 breaking changes that affect their specific scenario. Let me analyze their setup:\n\n1. They use `UseAzureSql` (Azure SQL provider)\n2. They have primitive collections (string[] Tags) and owned types mapped to JSON columns (currently nvarchar(max))\n3. They use `.Contains()` on `List<int>` in LINQ queries that currently use OPENJSON\n4. The project multi-targets net9.0 and net10.0\n5. They run `dotnet ef migrations add` without `--framework`\n\nLet me think about the known EF Core 10 breaking changes that would affect them:\n\n\nThe main issue is that EF Core 10 changes the default JSON column type for Azure SQL from `nvarchar(max)` to `nvarchar(4000)`, which will trigger migration changes for their existing JSON columns. Additionally, the query translation for `.Contains()` on primitive collections shifts from OPENJSON to JSON_VALUE/JSON_ARRAY functions, potentially affecting performance or compatibility with their current queries. The key breaking change with OPENJSON in EF Core 10 is how `.Contains()` translates parameterized collections—it's shifted from the untyped `OPENJSON` approach used in versions 8-9 to potentially using typed OPENJSON with explicit column definitions, or switching to inline constants for smaller collections. There's also a change around primitive collection defaults in Azure SQL, where they now cap at `nvarchar(4000)` instead of `nvarchar(max)`, which will trigger migration diffs.\n\nFor the multi-targeting tooling issue, the `dotnet ef` command now requires an explicit `--framework` flag when working with multi-targeted projects rather than attempting to pick a sensible default, which is a breaking change in how the tooling behaves. from untyped OPENJSON with CAST to typed OPENJSON, which can impact query performance and index selection. For **multi-target frameworks**: when a project targets multiple .NET versions, `dotnet ef migrations add` requires the `--framework` flag to specify which one to use, as the default selection behavior may have shifted in .NET 10.","outputTokens":2068,"requestId":"1421:1660D8:E0CE228:FA0552D:69EC0FC8"},"id":"a1f632a9-f704-49cd-836d-5f573e2d36f3","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:50:58.225Z","parentId":"809fc119-d7a2-472b-9872-2c7fc7ab3468"}
